<DESCRIPT>  PROFILE; HISTORY; SPORT; RADIO; CELEBRITY  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  LIFE OF RALPH; BORN: Oct. 28, 1945, at the San Francisco Children's Hospital
with a black eye. "They had to use forceps. That is attributable to my nasty
personality. Somebody was screwing around with me while I was still in the
womb. I was on the defensive, even before I popped out."  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  THE GRAPEVINE  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  See also related article on page 1L of this section.  </MEMO>
<TEXT>  FAMILY: Parents Louis and Gloria, married 42 years. "Typical Italian family.
Lots of screaming, hugging and kissing." Parents sold the family home in
Millbrae when dad was 62 and they moved to Sonoma. Louis died November 1985 at
age 65. Gloria, 67, lives in Sonoma near Ralph's sister.; SCHOOL: St.
Dunstan's School in Millbrae. "Thought I was the brightest kid in my class."
Graduated from Mills High in 1963. "My teen years consisted of throwing
Jujubees in the movies on Saturday night."; COLLEGE: Earned a degree in
political science from the University of San Francisco, 1967. "Huge,
embarrassing secret: I was on the basketball cheering squad. I wore tan shorts
with my skinny little calves." Earned an MBA in marketing from the Wharton
School of Finance and Commerce, 1970. Got an A on master's thesis: "Sexual
Motivation in Advertising."; WORK: Became account executive at Madison Avenue
advertising firm for 15 months. "Hated it. The day I quit (1971), I sobbed
while talking to my boss. I felt I was throwing away my whole education.";
SELF: In 1973 got immersed in Eastern philosophies. Looked into Krishna, Zen
Buddhism, Alan Watts, yoga, Ram Dass, meditation. From Watts (by way of G.K.
Chesterton), his sign-off: "Angels fly because they take themselves lightly."
Crazy about "All My Children."; WRITER: In 1974 met NBA center Bill Walton and
wrote a Sport Magazine article about Walton, the FBI and Patty Hearst. Also
wrote about Kenny Stabler, Bruce Jenner and Joe Thomas. "I was a good writer,
but I found it incredibly difficult to do."; RADIO: As a writer, was a guest
in 1977 on Sports Phone 68. "Program director loved me, but when I asked about
doing radio he said, 'Your voice sucks. Go to a speech therapist.' I did and
she said 'Your voice is high pitched, nasal and you have a slight lisp.' "
Moved to Hawaii and landed a $3 an hour talk show job. Returned to part-time
work with KICU-TV and KGO. In 1986 did drive-time sports commentary on KNBR-AM
and later backed up Dave Newhouse on Sports Phone 68 until taking over show in
June 1989.  </TEXT>
